## Instructions:
- Rate each of the 42 [Considerations] below from 1 to 7, where 1 is strongly disagree and 7 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 42 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 42 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. Street scene in Uppsala has changed for the worse since the beggars have come.
2. Sweden can not take responsibility for all the poor people in the world.
3. Many beggars are victims.
4. Beggars should not bring their children to Sweden but leave them at home so they can attend school.
5. EU migrants coming to Uppsala due to rumors of more support and shelter for the homeless.
6. The beggars trying to cheat me out of money by playing sick and poor even though they are not.
7. If we begin to help those who come here to beg for it will soon be even more.
8. We need to focus on giving them help in their homeland.
9. Before we assist foreign beggars, we must take care of our own Swedish homeless.
10. The beggars have it good here in Sweden and would rather live here. 
11. Home countries Romania and Bulgaria have a responsibility to improve the situation of their minority population.
12. Beggars can get away with things that you and I would not get away with.
13. The migrant beggars are eating way the Swedish welfare state
14. They should look for jobs instead of begging.
15. Beggars have the same values as us and therefore we have an obligation to help them with school, work, housing and food.
16. Politicians in Uppsala take no responsibility for the beggars.
17. We should take in more refugees in Sweden.
18. I have no responsibility for helping the begging Roma in Sweden.
19. It is our establishment which invites them to beg and take part of our social safety net.
20. The EU is responsible to handle the situation involving EU citizens crossing borders to beg.
21. The EU is powerless against Romania's shameless treatment of the Roma minority.
22. It's good to give money to the beggars
23. We must improve the beggars conditions when they are in Sweden.
24. The emergence of "parallel societies" and "slums" in Uppsala, is not acceptable.
25. The municipality is responsible for helping the begging EU citizens in Sweden.
26. Allowing street begging in some EU countries, including Sweden, does not facilitate Romania's efforts to achieve social inclusion and enhancing employability
27. Begging EU Citizens really want to go back to their country and not live in Sweden.
28. It is not OK to break Swedish law just because the offenders are poor.
29. Our tax money should go to the Swedes not to foreign beggars.
30. Begging on the streets of Uppsala is organized with connections to the criminal mafia.
31. I feel guilty that I have it good when I see a beggar.
32. Why don't we just treat the beggars the same as we do refugees? They are in the same situation.
33. Begging is caused by poverty and discrimination of minority groups in certain EU countries.
34. We can not help so much that we are sending the wrong signals.
35. I feel helpless when I see a beggar.
36. Beggars are victims of poverty in their home countries.
37.  Romania is failing to take responsibility for the Roma population.
38. Tourism in Sweden is damaged when the image of a clean and safe country no longer proves correct.
39. We should try the beggars to find other ways to help themselves.
40. There are too many beggars on the streets of Uppsala.
41. There is no ultimate responsibility for begging EU citizens.
42. The Swedish state is responsible for helping the begging Roma in Sweden.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 7 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 7, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 7 the option you support the least.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 7 ranks as integers, one rank per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 7 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. Forbid giving money to beggars
2. Provide accommodation for beggars (more)
3. Ban Illegal Settlements
4. Enforce existing laws without special consideration for beggars
5. Ban Begging within Sweden
6. Focus resources on addressing the the problem in source countries such as Romania
7. Deport any immigrants found begging on the streets who have stayed in Sweden longer than three months

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Support helping beggars but prioritize local issues and address root causes abroad.

## Instructions:
- Rate each of the 42 [Considerations] below from 1 to 12, where 1 is strongly disagree and 12 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 42 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 42 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. When it comes to the Bloomfield Track, it's not important to worry about what the future will hold
2. A long term perspective on the Bloomfield Track is essential.
3. In deciding on what to do with the Bloomfield Track I don't know whether it's more important to meet the needs of the community or the environment.
4. Using cars on the Bloomfield Track is bad for the rainforest.
5. No development should be permitted in World Heritage areas such as the Daintree.
6. The coral reefs along the foreshore below the Bloomfield Track are not badly affected by the road.
7. Whilst impacts on locals in the Bloomfield area are a concern, it is the broader community that should carry more weight when deciding what to do with the Bloomfield Track.
8. I would be worse off if more of the Daintree rainforest is protected.
9. If the Bloomfield Track is sealed (bitumenized) there will not be a rapid increase in environmentally damaging development in the Daintree area in the future It may even benefit the environment there.
10. The Bloomfield Track may not have been the best idea, but I guess there is probably little point in closing it now that it has been built.
11. I'm not sure if the future of the Bloomfield Track should be determined by locals, outsiders or both.
12. Everyone in Queensland is better off for having a road like the Bloomfield Track.
13. The road is just the 'thin edge of the wedge'. This may not happen for a long time, but it will happen.
14. Conservation in the Daintree area is worthwhile at whatever cost.
15. When it comes to the Bloomfield track, people living in Cairns are in no position to judge what the interests of the local residents of Bloomfield are.
16. Any decision about the Bloomfield Track will greatly affect people like me.
17. I have no idea what the people in the Bloomfield area think about the Bloomfield Track.
18. The Bloomfield Track issue is important for Queensland.
19. The future of the Bloomfield Track should be determined by everyone and not just by those who live in the Bloomfield area.
20. I don't know if improving the Bloomfield Track would lead to a rapid acceleration of development in the area to the detriment of the environment.
21. The fate of the Bloomfield Track is of no concern to me.
22. Erosion from the Bloomfield Track is permanently damaging the coral reefs that fringe the beaches below
23. The Wujal Wujal Community is better off now that the Bloomfield Track has been built.
24. Let's fix the problems in the Daintree just for now. The future will take care of itself.
25. I don't know what the people of Bloomfield think about the Bloomfield Track.
26. I don't like how development is creeping further and further North into the Daintree and beyond because of its effect on the environment.
27. I don't know how, but I think that there must be some way in which everybody benefits from protecting the rainforest near the Bloomfield Track.
28. If we don't take steps to protect the Daintree Rainforest future generations will miss out on the opportunity to experience the area as we do now.
29. If future generations could have their say about the Bloomfield track, they would be less concerned about the environmental impacts than many people make out.
30. The protection of plants and animals in the Daintree is OK so long as it doesn't affect me.
31. I don't really know who benefits most from the protection of Rainforest in the Daintree.
32. We don't need to worry too much about environmental damage in the Daintree region because future generations will be better able to deal with these problems than we are.
33. Laying bitumen on the Bloomfield Track would be beneficial for the environment
34. The Bloomfield Track is important because it allows quick access to remote areas of the North.
35. The more that it is possible for the average North Queensland resident can access the Bloomfield Track the better
36. I think that both short and long term perspectives are needed in deciding what should be done with the Bloomfield Track, but I don't know which one is more important.
37. Erosion from the Bloomfield Track does not cause siltation or damage to the fringing inshore reefs between Cape Tribulation and Cooktown
38. Native animals in the Daintree need protection because they have a right to life which cannot be traded against economic considerations.
39. There is no reason to believe that the Daintree Rainforest is under threat.
40. Economic development associated with the Bloomfield Track will provide more opportunities for future generations in North Queensland.
41. I'm concerned that I will be made worse off by any decision about the Bloomfield Track.
42. The most important use of the Bloomfield Track is for tourism.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 5 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 5, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 5 the option you support the least.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 5 ranks as integers, one rank per line following the format in the [Example output].

- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. Maintain the road in its current condition as a 4WD track.
2. Stabilize specific trouble spots, such as steep slopes, on the road but leave it as a 4WD track.
3. Upgrade the track to a bitumen road.
4. Close the road and rehabilitate it.
5. Upgrade the road, to a dirt road suitable for conventional vehicles.

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Favor stabilization and maintenance but oppose permanent upgrades or closure, preferring 4WD track stability.

## Instructions:
- Rate each of the 48 [Considerations] below from 1 to 11, where 1 is strongly disagree and 11 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 48 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. It would be a great thing if voters could vote on specific issues, not only on a whole party program at election time.
2. Democracy means that all policy is exposed to open discussion and debate in a public political space of all citizens before being put to a transparent, accountable vote.
3. The only time we are all equal is when we vote in the ballot box.
4. I don't know too much about democracy. I feel ridiculous voting.
5. Republicanism is a smokescreen for democratic treachery, incompetence and lunacy.
6. People are quite capable of processing and thinking about the vast majority of issues facing our society but as long as we are subjected to 'news lite' the level of political debate will remain facile. 
7. We should strengthen protections of the free press in order to facilitate a more open and publicly accountable government. 
8. Concluding that some races/cultures are better than others must be avoided.
9. If you want your vote to count for anything, then you need to not vote in ignorance, you need to know something about what you're being offered.
10. Sometimes I get a bit worried that there's a lot of small minority groups that tend to get a lot of the say
11. People get the government they deserve
12. The true function of government is to maintain peace and justice. This does not include interfering in private transactions of its electors.
13. We as individuals have a right, that's what democracy means to me
14. Governments can talk a great game about 'democracy'. They fall down, in practice, because they cannot accept any sharing of the power to influence decisions with those who might have different motives and ideas.
15. Our government is attempting to mould our society to the needs of a profit-oriented market
16. Democracy is a term which has lost much of its original meaning.
17. In the Senate there should be elected representatives who are not from the major parties but from smaller interest groups.
18. In Australia the rich have virtually unlimited access to the legal system and the capacity to use it to achieve their own ends.
19. I'm always cynical about government processes.
20. I don't want to be in a place where only a minority's viewpoint gets the right to say what's going to happen.
21. Our political system's strength is that it can change to meet changing circumstances.
22. If Australia is to recover from the horrible mess we are in at present, we will need leaders of high principles, who will govern with honesty, justice, and righteousness, fearlessly putting into practice the principles of the Bible.
23. Proportional Representation also forces parties to coalesce and moderates out the extreme political views. 
24. Until women are equally represented in Australian parliaments, we will not have a genuine representative democracy.
25. Democracy means we, the people, are responsible for what government does, or fails to do.
26. Low female participation rates compound the domination of the public realm by males.
27. The party system is the main obstruction to accountable politics.
28. The last thing we need is a Canberra 'Big Brother' telling us what we should read and hear.
29. We live in a great democracy.
30. Not voting is a form of expression. It's a way of telling parties that no one is offering policies that appeal to you.
31. Our community and nation should invoke a spirit that you are important, that you do have a way of influencing things.
32. The fundamental dynamic of Australian society is that it is one of evolution, not revolution.
33. We should not be afraid of disagreement. Indeed, an important feature of a liberal democracy is respect for conflicting ideas; difference is part of the human condition. 
34. I don't think there's anything wrong with people voting for their self-interest.
35. I suppose we do have an upper class and a lower class.
36. There's a dollar democracy that runs through our supposed democracy.
37. We suffer a Parliamentary Democracy and an archaic and conflict oriented, "two party system" where one of two main parties will manipulate us for the next few years. 
38. The people we elect are loyal not to we dumb bunnies who elected them, but the agenda and dogma of their party. 
39. There is a lot of consultation by govt – but who is listening?  And what power do they have to make changes?
40. Too few people have a lot of sway in the system.  Corporate lobbyists, vested interests, pork barrelling and contributions to political parties are all problematic.
41. The true believers are about decency in life, about a capacity to debate the issues and to receive different views.
42. The political system is remote and closed and the connection with elected representatives is difficult, they are often faceless.
43. A lot of people may be politically ignorant, but they believe what they see and hear on television, and that makes them vote the way they do. They have been brainwashed by the clever advertising people.
44. There is no real difference in ideological terms between the major parties and preference distributions are problematic.
45. Free markets work because individual people, cooperating peacefully and voluntarily through markets, can achieve much that politicians and bureaucrats cannot achieve using compulsion and direction.
46. I don't think we have a lot of input into legislation and a lot of things that are important.
47. We are a democratic country.
48. You don't have to wait three years to say 'I'm not happy with the job you did.' You can apply pressure, and enough people writing to the local member can turn the situation around.

2. Mental health issues require less urgency and fewer resources compared to physical health conditions.
3. Social media platforms should be required to have parental controls.
4. Mental health can be understood in different ways. A comprehensive definition of mental health should take into account social issues such as poverty, inequality, and discrimination.
5. Personal solutions (such as joining a yoga club) are more effective than government intervention in addressing mental health issues (such as having social workers or psychologists in schools).
6. Focusing on prevention strategies (e.g., government media campaigns) is essential to reducing the impact of stigma associated with mental health conditions.
7. Schools should play a crucial role in creating a supportive environment, both online and offline, to mitigate the negative impact of social media on mental health.
8. People with mental disorders should not be allowed to work with children.
9. Minors under the age of 16 should be legally prohibited from using social media.
10. Personal cultural or religious beliefs and preferences should guide the choice of treatment methods, including therapy and medication.
11. Individuals should take responsibility for their own mental well-being.
12. It is good that basic health insurance does not fully cover mental health care since only a few people need it.
13. Private mental health services are better than public ones, so Switzerland's mental health system should be entirely privatized.
14. To prevent people with mental health issues from feeling lonely or isolated, we should talk more about these topics in schools and workplaces to increase public understanding and sensitivity.
15. People should take responsibility for actively addressing their own biases and prejudices against individuals with mental health disorders.
16. More government funding is needed to improve mental health services and their accessibility, especially for marginalized people subject to socioeconomic disparities.
17. Being poor, living far from urban centers, or being a victim of racism are examples of factors that can influence a person's willingness to seek help for mental health problems.
18. Improving working or study conditions does not impact people's mental health in any way.
19. Mental health problems are solely medical in nature and not a social issue.
20. Investing in mental health services in schools and workplaces (for example, having social workers in facilities) is essential to prevent negative mental health outcomes.

## Instructions:
- Rate each of the 45 [Considerations] below from 1 to 11, where 1 is strongly disagree and 11 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 45 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 45 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. I don't want the implementation of new energy technologies to disrupt my way of life.
2. The petroleum age is far from over, we will still be able to keep finding more oil.
3. It is very hard to trust all these so-called experts arguing for one energy technology or another, especially when they, or their bosses, are just in it to make money.
4. Coal gasification is needed to produce hydrogen on the scale required for a possible transition to a hydrogen-based economy.
5. Energy technologies are pretty complex, so I leave it to the experts. 
6. Renewables are part of the long-term solution, but for the foreseeable future, they just can't do the job.
7. The urgency of addressing greenhouse emissions cannot stay on back burner for too much longer. So we need to find a solution quickly, such as CO2 capture and storage.
8.  If Australia mines uranium, the country should be able to generate power from it.
9. Coal-powered energy needs to be minimised because of its high greenhouse gas emissions.
10. The limited strategic and technical insight that is so entrenched in Australia is limiting the development of innovative energy technologies.
11. Fuzzy-headed thinking about alternative energy sources seems not to appreciate the need for certainty of supply and excess capacity to keep economies growing.
12. If the cost of greenhouse gas emissions is factored in, the cost of renewables compared to coal isn't so big.
13. Prices of alternative energy will fall as technology improves.
14. Natural gas is the bridging fuel between the oil economy and the hydrogen economy.
15. Governments must fund new infrastructure investment in the face of uncertainty in the economics of energy technologies.
16. Combining technologies in the energy sector is a much more promising and more productive approach than relying on a single approach. 
17. Australia doesn't support alternative energy opportunities. Industry comes along and says, 'Have I got something for you' (such as carbon sequestration, or a new power station) and they get government subsidies to do it.
18. Local energy solutions such as windfarms are good for jobs, local economies and tourism.
19. Many big ticket solutions to energy problems that we don't understand are just too risky.
20. Nuclear is the inevitable replacement for old hydrocarbon technology. It is cost-competitive with coal and will cogenerate potable water and hydrogen also at societally acceptable costs.
21. Climate change considerations have no role in the development of national and global energy policies.
22. Australia should  turn more attention to biomass energy sources because it is CO2 neutral (the carbon dioxide used by the growing plants is released when they are burned).
23. Solar power is pointless because it can't guarantee constant supply, for obvious reasons: the sun doesn't always shine.
24. Rather than look at costly renewable energy a more fair-dinkum strategy would be to encourage technology that captures greenhouse emissions like carbon dioxide.
25. Any tax to reduce greenhouse gas emissions will have a detrimental economic effect on the nation.
26. Geothermal or hot rock technology will provide a reliable and unlimited and cheap energy source.
27. Using biomass from crops has significant expansion potential and would be good for the rural industry.
28. You could have a wind farm across all of the outback that would kill every kookaburra, but it wouldn't provide the baseload power we need.
29. Reducing our reliance on oil would be good for the economy and the environment.
30. Wind power has its downsides — it is highly visible and can kill birds. The fact is though, that any man-made structure can kill birds.	
31. There is no need make expensive investments in technological changes within the energy sector.
32. Apart from coal, natural gas is the only other potentially reliable source of power for the state.
33. Any return on geosequestration is 15 to 20 years off, whereas the proven technology of renewable energy offers immediate gains.
34. Energy technologies such as nuclear power and geosequestration are too risky. It's better to improve the technologies that we already have.
35. Can we be confident, that if we store CO2 the storage facility is going to hold it forever? That's really the issue. And I don't think anybody can answer that question.
36. Nuclear power is a more proven technology than it was 30 years ago. In reality atomic power generation can be a very safe system if designed and operated correctly.
37. I'm not pro-nuclear, I'm not pro-coal, I'm not pro-wind, I'm not pro any kind of generation. I'm pro-energy conservation through changes to our behavioural and design practices.
38. Environmental, reliability and cost issues will limit the adoption of large-scale  of certain renewable technologies. 
39. Energy is going to get costly so we had better start investing in alternatives.
40. Our present energy system is so cheap precisely because it is unsustainable.
41. We need coal because it is a cheap and reliable energy source.
42. Australia spends too much on research and development in energy technologies.
43. Reducing greenhouse gases should not mean prices have to go up.
44. Renewable sources do not have the potential to meet our future energy needs as they stand.
45. Nuclear has a few dangers, but they're trivial compared with the dangers of emitting greenhouse gases and letting global warming happen.

34. I'm worried that human genome editing will widen the gap between those who can afford it and those who can't.
35. I think it's okay to use genome editing to change someone's appearance.
36. If genome editing is proven to be safe, then I see no reason to oppose it.
37. Parents want 'designer babies' with certain traits out of vanity.
38. I'm concerned that genome editing will be used as a quick techno-fix without actually dealing with real problems.
39. I don't think we know enough about genetic diseases or the long term consequences of genome editing
40. Science and technology have too much control over our lives.
41. The idea of editing the human genome is scary.
42. Decisions about the use of genome editing are best left to the experts.
43. Editing genes that will be inherited is problematic because it means making decisions for future people who don't exist yet.

## Instructions:
- Rate each of the 45 [Considerations] below from 1 to 11, where 1 is strongly disagree and 11 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 45 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 45 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. We need to clean up the bureaucratic maze that stops our professional foresters from being able to do the work that they are trained to do.
2. Forest restoration projects should be done in all areas of the forest including roadless and wilderness areas.
3. Aggressive fire suppression has caused the majority of the problems regarding  fires. 
4. Land managers should return public forest land to natural conditions and fire cycles that are specific to each forest-type.
5. We should not manipulate nature by restoring forest conditions.
6. Forest health needs restoring after decades of government mismanagement.
7. Federal land management procedures are so complex that they prevent timely action to address ecological crises on public lands.
8. A diameter cap should be placed on all thinning projects to ensure large trees are not cut.
9. To make thinning projects cost effective, private logging companies must be able to log larger trees.
10. Forest lands should be brought back to their state before human intervention began.
11. Returning forests to presettlement conditions ignores the need for wildlife that are adapted to current forest conditions by mandating drastic thinning virtually overnight. 
12. We need to allow forest managers to determine how to improve forest health to minimize fire damage and loss.
13. The government is advancing timber sales in the name of ecological restoration.
14. We have to move forward with large-scale restoration-based fuel reduction and learn as we go.
15. Natural resources must be developed for the benefit of the plain American citizen.
16. Traditional, sustainable forestry that benefits local economies and maintains rural livelihoods is much better than large scale corporate forestry.
17. Old Growth protection is necessary in order to preserve and protect the viability of species dependent upon Old Growth ecosystems.
18. Humans are a part of the environment. We need to learn how to live sustainably with that environment as much as possible. 
19. The main issue in forest management is to protect loss of life and property due to catastrophic wildfire. 
20. Using citizen participation in forest management is very important for basing decisions on different ideas and cultural values along with science. 
21. Fire risk reduction projects should clearly focus on the wildland-urban interface, avoiding treatments in roadless areas.
22. Environmental organizations have moved the management of our forests to where it is being done by emotion and not by science.
23. Demonizing fire is a mistake: we must accept risks of fire damage to property and implement controlled burning.
24. Forest health means jobs.
25. The increased density of forests in the West has not damaged ecosystems.
26. Forests must contribute to the economic stability of forest-dependent communities.  There are many job opportunities and value-added products that come out of the forest such as wood for art, vigas for building homes, wildlife for food, herbs for medicine, and grass for livestock.
27. Needless red tape and lawsuits delay effective implementation of forest health projects on public lands.
28. Prescribed burning is needed to restore fire-adapted ecosystems.
29. All fuels treatment projects on public lands should comply with existing environmental laws even if compliance slows implementation.
30. We need to be cautious: the solution is there, but we still have a lot to learn. If we just jump in, we're going to make mistakes.
31. Large trees must be removed in order to create openings for wildlife habitat. 
32. We need to experiment with a range of treatments that could meet restoration goals. 
33. Prescribed burns are a flawed idea, especially when there are other practices available for restoration.
34. Thinning efforts should focus entirely on the small trees that make up the vast majority of the fire risk in the forest. 
35. Small scale thinning projects should give the communities involved pride in taking part in a sustainable forest management plan, and it also allows the traditional communities to realize a boost to their fragile economies.
36. Fire is a natural and vital component of most western forest ecosystems.
37. Federal agencies need to restore public trust through transparency in project intent, development and implementation.
38. If an action is determined to be necessary to control a wildfire, save lives and/or property, and ensure that fire crews can do their jobs safely and efficiently, then it is appropriate to act even if it results in the take of an endangered species.
39. Stakeholders in forest management should work together to define management objectives more by experiments and adaptive management. 
40. Forest management involves restoring ecosystem function and processes that maintain ecosystems over the long run. 
41. People should take what is needed from forests, but in a context of stewardship and sustainable use and interaction with nature. 
42. We need active forest management on our public lands, through thinning and prescribed burns to reduce the unnatural buildup of fuels.
43. Without public participation there will be conflict, whereas participation leads to cooperation.
44. Science is the most important component informing all management decisions — more so than social, cultural and economic considerations.
45. Federal forest management policy should make it easier for loggers to thin out backcountry forests by easing regulatory restrictions and making it harder for interest groups to stop or delay that work.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 7 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 7, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 7 the option you support the least.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 7 ranks as integers, one rank per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 7 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. Management that favors the protection of wildlife and wildlife habitat.
2. No fire or fuels management. Leaving the forests as they stand without active management.
3. Management that favors aggressive reduction of hazardous fuels
4. Management that favors treatments to restore structure, function and composition of the forest to presettlement conditions, and allowing the introduction of fire as a natural disturbance.
5. Management that favors local-based harvesting for fuel and timber needs.
6. Management that favors thinning treatments to realize economic gain.
7. Management that prioritizes the location and level of treatments favoring both ecological and social values (i.e. wildlife, watersheds, community protection, special cultural places).

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.

response: Favor active management, prioritizing ecological values with some local input and controlled burns.

## [Considerations]:
1. People should take what is needed from forests, but in a context of stewardship and sustainable use and interaction with nature. 
2. We need to experiment with a range of treatments that could meet restoration goals. 
3. If an action is determined to be necessary to control a wildfire, save lives and/or property, and ensure that fire crews can do their jobs safely and efficiently, then it is appropriate to act even if it results in the take of an endangered species.
4. To make thinning projects cost effective, private logging companies must be able to log larger trees.
5. Environmental organizations have moved the management of our forests to where it is being done by emotion and not by science.
6. We need to allow forest managers to determine how to improve forest health to minimize fire damage and loss.
7. We should not manipulate nature by restoring forest conditions.
8. Humans are a part of the environment. We need to learn how to live sustainably with that environment as much as possible. 
9. Forest health means jobs.
10. Needless red tape and lawsuits delay effective implementation of forest health projects on public lands.
11. Stakeholders in forest management should work together to define management objectives more by experiments and adaptive management. 
12. Forest restoration projects should be done in all areas of the forest including roadless and wilderness areas.
13. Federal land management procedures are so complex that they prevent timely action to address ecological crises on public lands.
14. We need active forest management on our public lands, through thinning and prescribed burns to reduce the unnatural buildup of fuels.
15. Returning forests to presettlement conditions ignores the need for wildlife that are adapted to current forest conditions by mandating drastic thinning virtually overnight. 
16. Fire risk reduction projects should clearly focus on the wildland-urban interface, avoiding treatments in roadless areas.
17. The government is advancing timber sales in the name of ecological restoration.
18. Traditional, sustainable forestry that benefits local economies and maintains rural livelihoods is much better than large scale corporate forestry.
19. The main issue in forest management is to protect loss of life and property due to catastrophic wildfire. 
20. Science is the most important component informing all management decisions — more so than social, cultural and economic considerations.
21. Aggressive fire suppression has caused the majority of the problems regarding  fires. 
22. We need to clean up the bureaucratic maze that stops our professional foresters from being able to do the work that they are trained to do.
23. Large trees must be removed in order to create openings for wildlife habitat. 
24. Using citizen participation in forest management is very important for basing decisions on different ideas and cultural values along with science. 
25. Federal forest management policy should make it easier for loggers to thin out backcountry forests by easing regulatory restrictions and making it harder for interest groups to stop or delay that work.
26. Thinning efforts should focus entirely on the small trees that make up the vast majority of the fire risk in the forest. 
27. Forest management involves restoring ecosystem function and processes that maintain ecosystems over the long run. 
28. Federal agencies need to restore public trust through transparency in project intent, development and implementation.
29. All fuels treatment projects on public lands should comply with existing environmental laws even if compliance slows implementation.
30. Natural resources must be developed for the benefit of the plain American citizen.
31. Land managers should return public forest land to natural conditions and fire cycles that are specific to each forest-type.
32. Prescribed burning is needed to restore fire-adapted ecosystems.
33. The increased density of forests in the West has not damaged ecosystems.
34. We need to be cautious: the solution is there, but we still have a lot to learn. If we just jump in, we're going to make mistakes.
35. Without public participation there will be conflict, whereas participation leads to cooperation.
36. Forests must contribute to the economic stability of forest-dependent communities.  There are many job opportunities and value-added products that come out of the forest such as wood for art, vigas for building homes, wildlife for food, herbs for medicine, and grass for livestock.
37. We have to move forward with large-scale restoration-based fuel reduction and learn as we go.
38. Forest lands should be brought back to their state before human intervention began.
39. Old Growth protection is necessary in order to preserve and protect the viability of species dependent upon Old Growth ecosystems.
40. Fire is a natural and vital component of most western forest ecosystems.
41. Demonizing fire is a mistake: we must accept risks of fire damage to property and implement controlled burning.
42. Prescribed burns are a flawed idea, especially when there are other practices available for restoration.
43. Small scale thinning projects should give the communities involved pride in taking part in a sustainable forest management plan, and it also allows the traditional communities to realize a boost to their fragile economies.
44. A diameter cap should be placed on all thinning projects to ensure large trees are not cut.
45. Forest health needs restoring after decades of government mismanagement.

- Rate each of the 32 [Considerations] below from 1 to 7, where 1 is strongly disagree and 7 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 32 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 32 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. Authorities have the resources they need to effectively adapt to climate change.
2. It doesn't make much sense for me to do anything to solve the problem. No one else is doing anything.
3. I don't know what to do. I am very worried and would like to do something, but I don't have a realistic set of actions that would truly make a difference.
4. It is necessary to have strong on-the-ground disaster response capabilities to deal with extreme weather conditions.
5. Authorities should receive additional funding to strengthen measures against emergencies and weather-related disasters such as floods.
6. Switzerland is particularly vulnerable to climate change, and it is in our interest to contribute to an effective global solution.
7. It is important to support vulnerable groups (the elderly, children, people with disabilities, low-income individuals) as they have fewer resources to deal with the impacts of climate change.
8. The planning of measures to tackle climate change should focus primarily on extreme weather events such as droughts and floods.
9. There is no urgent need to prepare for an increase in illnesses and deaths caused by high temperatures.
10. Rising insurance costs are a serious problem related to climate change.
11. We should focus on protecting human systems rather than protecting ecosystems.
12. I'm not going to do anything about climate change because it's not an important issue.
13. Some countries or regions of the world will be more affected by climate change than others, but this is not our top priority.
14. Doing something to reduce emissions seems a bit hopeless to me, but I just want to feel like I'm doing my best.
15. It is important to prepare for the migration of people displaced by the effects of climate change.
16. We need to take into account the negative effects of climate change on local businesses.
17. Even if Switzerland were to reduce all its CO₂ emissions, global warming would continue.
18. It is NOT necessary to involve society in deciding which key issues are important for climate change adaptation planning.
19. The urban heat island effect must be tackled with measures such as planting trees.
20. Climate change is natural; there is no need to worry.
21. There is not enough information to conclusively say that climate change is real.
22. The melting of Alpine glaciers is not a real problem for our daily lives.
23. It is important to focus on adaptation measures that take into account the country's economic future.
24. Climate change is primarily caused by human activity.
25. It is difficult to trust scientists' reports on climate change.
26. Planning climate change response measures requires a global approach that considers a wide range of interventions rather than specific individual actions.
27. It is difficult to trust what the media report about climate change.
28. It is certain to say that climate change exists.
29. I believe that the impact we can achieve as individuals in Switzerland is so small that our actions are useless.
30. Health systems must prepare for both the physical health impacts of climate change (e.g., heat stroke) and the mental health impacts (e.g., farmers losing their crops).
31. It is difficult to trust government reports on climate change.
32. Society should be included in the discussion on climate change adaptation.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 7 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 7, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 7 the option you support the least.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 7 ranks as integers, one rank per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 7 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. "Policies that involve a moderate reduction in CO₂ emissions (e.g., reducing emissions by 25% to 50% over the next 10 years)."
2. Leave the policy settings as they are.
3. Adaptation policies that target individual, small business or community-based actions (e.g., support the installation of alternative energy generators, insulation, water use efficiency)
4. Adaptation policies and expenditure. Planning controls and emergency response programs.
5. Policies that emphasise economic growth over climate change adaptation or mitigation.
6. Preparing for climate risk through the development of new approaches and technologies that enhance resilience to the impacts of climate variability or change.
7. "Policies that involve a radical reduction in CO₂ emissions (e.g., reducing emissions by 50% to 100% over the next 10 years)."

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Moderate emission reductions and targeted adaptations are prioritized; economic growth less favored; radical reductions seen as less practical.

## Instructions:

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. Apart from coal, natural gas is the only other potentially reliable source of power for the state.
2. Reducing greenhouse gases should not mean prices have to go up.
3. Prices of alternative energy will fall as technology improves.
4. I don't want the implementation of new energy technologies to disrupt my way of life.
5.  If Australia mines uranium, the country should be able to generate power from it.
6. Nuclear has a few dangers, but they're trivial compared with the dangers of emitting greenhouse gases and letting global warming happen.
7. Climate change considerations have no role in the development of national and global energy policies.
8. The urgency of addressing greenhouse emissions cannot stay on back burner for too much longer. So we need to find a solution quickly, such as CO2 capture and storage.
9. There is no need make expensive investments in technological changes within the energy sector.
10. Many big ticket solutions to energy problems that we don't understand are just too risky.
11. If the cost of greenhouse gas emissions is factored in, the cost of renewables compared to coal isn't so big.
12. Wind power has its downsides — it is highly visible and can kill birds. The fact is though, that any man-made structure can kill birds.	
13. Our present energy system is so cheap precisely because it is unsustainable.
14. The petroleum age is far from over, we will still be able to keep finding more oil.
15. Reducing our reliance on oil would be good for the economy and the environment.
16. Any return on geosequestration is 15 to 20 years off, whereas the proven technology of renewable energy offers immediate gains.
17. Any tax to reduce greenhouse gas emissions will have a detrimental economic effect on the nation.
18. We need coal because it is a cheap and reliable energy source.
19. The limited strategic and technical insight that is so entrenched in Australia is limiting the development of innovative energy technologies.
20. Can we be confident, that if we store CO2 the storage facility is going to hold it forever? That's really the issue. And I don't think anybody can answer that question.
21. Local energy solutions such as windfarms are good for jobs, local economies and tourism.
22. Nuclear power is a more proven technology than it was 30 years ago. In reality atomic power generation can be a very safe system if designed and operated correctly.
23. Environmental, reliability and cost issues will limit the adoption of large-scale  of certain renewable technologies. 
24. Renewable sources do not have the potential to meet our future energy needs as they stand.
25. Australia doesn't support alternative energy opportunities. Industry comes along and says, 'Have I got something for you' (such as carbon sequestration, or a new power station) and they get government subsidies to do it.
26. Australia should  turn more attention to biomass energy sources because it is CO2 neutral (the carbon dioxide used by the growing plants is released when they are burned).
27. Australia spends too much on research and development in energy technologies.
28. Nuclear is the inevitable replacement for old hydrocarbon technology. It is cost-competitive with coal and will cogenerate potable water and hydrogen also at societally acceptable costs.
29. Coal-powered energy needs to be minimised because of its high greenhouse gas emissions.
30. Using biomass from crops has significant expansion potential and would be good for the rural industry.
31. You could have a wind farm across all of the outback that would kill every kookaburra, but it wouldn't provide the baseload power we need.
32. Solar power is pointless because it can't guarantee constant supply, for obvious reasons: the sun doesn't always shine.
33. Governments must fund new infrastructure investment in the face of uncertainty in the economics of energy technologies.
34. Combining technologies in the energy sector is a much more promising and more productive approach than relying on a single approach. 
35. Energy is going to get costly so we had better start investing in alternatives.
36. Coal gasification is needed to produce hydrogen on the scale required for a possible transition to a hydrogen-based economy.
37. Renewables are part of the long-term solution, but for the foreseeable future, they just can't do the job.
38. Geothermal or hot rock technology will provide a reliable and unlimited and cheap energy source.
39. Energy technologies such as nuclear power and geosequestration are too risky. It's better to improve the technologies that we already have.
40. Energy technologies are pretty complex, so I leave it to the experts. 
41. Rather than look at costly renewable energy a more fair-dinkum strategy would be to encourage technology that captures greenhouse emissions like carbon dioxide.
42. Natural gas is the bridging fuel between the oil economy and the hydrogen economy.
43. I'm not pro-nuclear, I'm not pro-coal, I'm not pro-wind, I'm not pro any kind of generation. I'm pro-energy conservation through changes to our behavioural and design practices.
44. Fuzzy-headed thinking about alternative energy sources seems not to appreciate the need for certainty of supply and excess capacity to keep economies growing.
45. It is very hard to trust all these so-called experts arguing for one energy technology or another, especially when they, or their bosses, are just in it to make money.

## [Considerations]:
1. Many big ticket solutions to energy problems that we don't understand are just too risky.
2. Fuzzy-headed thinking about alternative energy sources seems not to appreciate the need for certainty of supply and excess capacity to keep economies growing.
3. Rather than look at costly renewable energy a more fair-dinkum strategy would be to encourage technology that captures greenhouse emissions like carbon dioxide.
4. Apart from coal, natural gas is the only other potentially reliable source of power for the state.
5. Australia should  turn more attention to biomass energy sources because it is CO2 neutral (the carbon dioxide used by the growing plants is released when they are burned).
6.  If Australia mines uranium, the country should be able to generate power from it.
7. Coal-powered energy needs to be minimised because of its high greenhouse gas emissions.
8. Solar power is pointless because it can't guarantee constant supply, for obvious reasons: the sun doesn't always shine.
9. The limited strategic and technical insight that is so entrenched in Australia is limiting the development of innovative energy technologies.
10. Natural gas is the bridging fuel between the oil economy and the hydrogen economy.
11. Energy technologies such as nuclear power and geosequestration are too risky. It's better to improve the technologies that we already have.
12. Climate change considerations have no role in the development of national and global energy policies.
13. Our present energy system is so cheap precisely because it is unsustainable.
14. Renewable sources do not have the potential to meet our future energy needs as they stand.
15. Combining technologies in the energy sector is a much more promising and more productive approach than relying on a single approach. 
16. I don't want the implementation of new energy technologies to disrupt my way of life.
17. Energy technologies are pretty complex, so I leave it to the experts. 
18. The urgency of addressing greenhouse emissions cannot stay on back burner for too much longer. So we need to find a solution quickly, such as CO2 capture and storage.
19. You could have a wind farm across all of the outback that would kill every kookaburra, but it wouldn't provide the baseload power we need.
20. Any return on geosequestration is 15 to 20 years off, whereas the proven technology of renewable energy offers immediate gains.
21. Nuclear power is a more proven technology than it was 30 years ago. In reality atomic power generation can be a very safe system if designed and operated correctly.
22. Environmental, reliability and cost issues will limit the adoption of large-scale  of certain renewable technologies. 
23. Geothermal or hot rock technology will provide a reliable and unlimited and cheap energy source.
24. Prices of alternative energy will fall as technology improves.
25. Renewables are part of the long-term solution, but for the foreseeable future, they just can't do the job.
26. Using biomass from crops has significant expansion potential and would be good for the rural industry.
27. Can we be confident, that if we store CO2 the storage facility is going to hold it forever? That's really the issue. And I don't think anybody can answer that question.
28. Reducing our reliance on oil would be good for the economy and the environment.
29. Governments must fund new infrastructure investment in the face of uncertainty in the economics of energy technologies.
30. There is no need make expensive investments in technological changes within the energy sector.
31. The petroleum age is far from over, we will still be able to keep finding more oil.
32. Wind power has its downsides — it is highly visible and can kill birds. The fact is though, that any man-made structure can kill birds.	
33. Australia doesn't support alternative energy opportunities. Industry comes along and says, 'Have I got something for you' (such as carbon sequestration, or a new power station) and they get government subsidies to do it.
34. Nuclear is the inevitable replacement for old hydrocarbon technology. It is cost-competitive with coal and will cogenerate potable water and hydrogen also at societally acceptable costs.
35. Local energy solutions such as windfarms are good for jobs, local economies and tourism.
36. Australia spends too much on research and development in energy technologies.
37. I'm not pro-nuclear, I'm not pro-coal, I'm not pro-wind, I'm not pro any kind of generation. I'm pro-energy conservation through changes to our behavioural and design practices.
38. We need coal because it is a cheap and reliable energy source.
39. Nuclear has a few dangers, but they're trivial compared with the dangers of emitting greenhouse gases and letting global warming happen.
40. Reducing greenhouse gases should not mean prices have to go up.
41. If the cost of greenhouse gas emissions is factored in, the cost of renewables compared to coal isn't so big.
42. Coal gasification is needed to produce hydrogen on the scale required for a possible transition to a hydrogen-based economy.
43. It is very hard to trust all these so-called experts arguing for one energy technology or another, especially when they, or their bosses, are just in it to make money.
44. Energy is going to get costly so we had better start investing in alternatives.
45. Any tax to reduce greenhouse gas emissions will have a detrimental economic effect on the nation.

- Rate each of the 45 [Considerations] below from 1 to 11, where 1 is strongly disagree and 11 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 45 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 45 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. The petroleum age is far from over, we will still be able to keep finding more oil.
2. Solar power is pointless because it can't guarantee constant supply, for obvious reasons: the sun doesn't always shine.
3. It is very hard to trust all these so-called experts arguing for one energy technology or another, especially when they, or their bosses, are just in it to make money.
4. Natural gas is the bridging fuel between the oil economy and the hydrogen economy.
5. Local energy solutions such as windfarms are good for jobs, local economies and tourism.
6. I don't want the implementation of new energy technologies to disrupt my way of life.
7. Renewable sources do not have the potential to meet our future energy needs as they stand.
8. Nuclear has a few dangers, but they're trivial compared with the dangers of emitting greenhouse gases and letting global warming happen.
9. Apart from coal, natural gas is the only other potentially reliable source of power for the state.
10. Australia doesn't support alternative energy opportunities. Industry comes along and says, 'Have I got something for you' (such as carbon sequestration, or a new power station) and they get government subsidies to do it.
11. Prices of alternative energy will fall as technology improves.
12. There is no need make expensive investments in technological changes within the energy sector.
13.  If Australia mines uranium, the country should be able to generate power from it.
14. The limited strategic and technical insight that is so entrenched in Australia is limiting the development of innovative energy technologies.
15. You could have a wind farm across all of the outback that would kill every kookaburra, but it wouldn't provide the baseload power we need.
16. Reducing our reliance on oil would be good for the economy and the environment.
17. Energy is going to get costly so we had better start investing in alternatives.
18. Can we be confident, that if we store CO2 the storage facility is going to hold it forever? That's really the issue. And I don't think anybody can answer that question.
19. Renewables are part of the long-term solution, but for the foreseeable future, they just can't do the job.
20. Environmental, reliability and cost issues will limit the adoption of large-scale  of certain renewable technologies. 
21. Australia should  turn more attention to biomass energy sources because it is CO2 neutral (the carbon dioxide used by the growing plants is released when they are burned).
22. Any tax to reduce greenhouse gas emissions will have a detrimental economic effect on the nation.
23. Fuzzy-headed thinking about alternative energy sources seems not to appreciate the need for certainty of supply and excess capacity to keep economies growing.
24. Using biomass from crops has significant expansion potential and would be good for the rural industry.
25. Climate change considerations have no role in the development of national and global energy policies.
26. If the cost of greenhouse gas emissions is factored in, the cost of renewables compared to coal isn't so big.
27. Geothermal or hot rock technology will provide a reliable and unlimited and cheap energy source.
28. Reducing greenhouse gases should not mean prices have to go up.
29. Energy technologies are pretty complex, so I leave it to the experts. 
30. Wind power has its downsides — it is highly visible and can kill birds. The fact is though, that any man-made structure can kill birds.	
31. Any return on geosequestration is 15 to 20 years off, whereas the proven technology of renewable energy offers immediate gains.
32. Nuclear power is a more proven technology than it was 30 years ago. In reality atomic power generation can be a very safe system if designed and operated correctly.
33. Governments must fund new infrastructure investment in the face of uncertainty in the economics of energy technologies.
34. Coal gasification is needed to produce hydrogen on the scale required for a possible transition to a hydrogen-based economy.
35. Rather than look at costly renewable energy a more fair-dinkum strategy would be to encourage technology that captures greenhouse emissions like carbon dioxide.
36. Coal-powered energy needs to be minimised because of its high greenhouse gas emissions.
37. The urgency of addressing greenhouse emissions cannot stay on back burner for too much longer. So we need to find a solution quickly, such as CO2 capture and storage.
38. Combining technologies in the energy sector is a much more promising and more productive approach than relying on a single approach. 
39. We need coal because it is a cheap and reliable energy source.
40. Energy technologies such as nuclear power and geosequestration are too risky. It's better to improve the technologies that we already have.
41. I'm not pro-nuclear, I'm not pro-coal, I'm not pro-wind, I'm not pro any kind of generation. I'm pro-energy conservation through changes to our behavioural and design practices.
42. Many big ticket solutions to energy problems that we don't understand are just too risky.
43. Nuclear is the inevitable replacement for old hydrocarbon technology. It is cost-competitive with coal and will cogenerate potable water and hydrogen also at societally acceptable costs.
44. Our present energy system is so cheap precisely because it is unsustainable.
45. Australia spends too much on research and development in energy technologies.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 9 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 9, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 9 the option you support the least.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 9 ranks as integers, one rank per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 9 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. Nuclear Energy
2. Coal with CO2 Burial
3. Geothermal Energy
4. Hydroelectric
5. Natural Gas
6. Biomass
7. Coal
8. Wind
9. Solar Energy

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Nuclear preferred; solar and wind lower due to variability; coal and gas low due to emissions; geothermal and bioenergy moderate.

2. Renewables are part of the long-term solution, but for the foreseeable future, they just can't do the job.
3. Our present energy system is so cheap precisely because it is unsustainable.
4. Fuzzy-headed thinking about alternative energy sources seems not to appreciate the need for certainty of supply and excess capacity to keep economies growing.
5. I don't want the implementation of new energy technologies to disrupt my way of life.
6. Natural gas is the bridging fuel between the oil economy and the hydrogen economy.
7. If the cost of greenhouse gas emissions is factored in, the cost of renewables compared to coal isn't so big.
8. Coal gasification is needed to produce hydrogen on the scale required for a possible transition to a hydrogen-based economy.
9. I'm not pro-nuclear, I'm not pro-coal, I'm not pro-wind, I'm not pro any kind of generation. I'm pro-energy conservation through changes to our behavioural and design practices.
10. Governments must fund new infrastructure investment in the face of uncertainty in the economics of energy technologies.
11. Coal-powered energy needs to be minimised because of its high greenhouse gas emissions.
12. Nuclear is the inevitable replacement for old hydrocarbon technology. It is cost-competitive with coal and will cogenerate potable water and hydrogen also at societally acceptable costs.
13.  If Australia mines uranium, the country should be able to generate power from it.
14. Nuclear power is a more proven technology than it was 30 years ago. In reality atomic power generation can be a very safe system if designed and operated correctly.
15. It is very hard to trust all these so-called experts arguing for one energy technology or another, especially when they, or their bosses, are just in it to make money.
16. Climate change considerations have no role in the development of national and global energy policies.
17. Energy technologies such as nuclear power and geosequestration are too risky. It's better to improve the technologies that we already have.
18. Energy is going to get costly so we had better start investing in alternatives.
19. Can we be confident, that if we store CO2 the storage facility is going to hold it forever? That's really the issue. And I don't think anybody can answer that question.
20. Prices of alternative energy will fall as technology improves.
21. Solar power is pointless because it can't guarantee constant supply, for obvious reasons: the sun doesn't always shine.
22. Any return on geosequestration is 15 to 20 years off, whereas the proven technology of renewable energy offers immediate gains.
23. Geothermal or hot rock technology will provide a reliable and unlimited and cheap energy source.
24. Energy technologies are pretty complex, so I leave it to the experts. 
25. Australia spends too much on research and development in energy technologies.
26. Rather than look at costly renewable energy a more fair-dinkum strategy would be to encourage technology that captures greenhouse emissions like carbon dioxide.
27. Nuclear has a few dangers, but they're trivial compared with the dangers of emitting greenhouse gases and letting global warming happen.
28. Environmental, reliability and cost issues will limit the adoption of large-scale  of certain renewable technologies. 
29. The limited strategic and technical insight that is so entrenched in Australia is limiting the development of innovative energy technologies.
30. Reducing greenhouse gases should not mean prices have to go up.
31. Wind power has its downsides — it is highly visible and can kill birds. The fact is though, that any man-made structure can kill birds.	
32. There is no need make expensive investments in technological changes within the energy sector.
33. Reducing our reliance on oil would be good for the economy and the environment.
34. Renewable sources do not have the potential to meet our future energy needs as they stand.
35. Combining technologies in the energy sector is a much more promising and more productive approach than relying on a single approach. 
36. You could have a wind farm across all of the outback that would kill every kookaburra, but it wouldn't provide the baseload power we need.
37. Many big ticket solutions to energy problems that we don't understand are just too risky.
38. Australia should  turn more attention to biomass energy sources because it is CO2 neutral (the carbon dioxide used by the growing plants is released when they are burned).
39. Local energy solutions such as windfarms are good for jobs, local economies and tourism.
40. The urgency of addressing greenhouse emissions cannot stay on back burner for too much longer. So we need to find a solution quickly, such as CO2 capture and storage.
41. Any tax to reduce greenhouse gas emissions will have a detrimental economic effect on the nation.
42. Australia doesn't support alternative energy opportunities. Industry comes along and says, 'Have I got something for you' (such as carbon sequestration, or a new power station) and they get government subsidies to do it.
43. We need coal because it is a cheap and reliable energy source.
44. Using biomass from crops has significant expansion potential and would be good for the rural industry.
45. The petroleum age is far from over, we will still be able to keep finding more oil.

19. I do not mind if my sample is connected to my name and medical information.
20. Genetic studies of race on ethnic or cultural groups will lead to the discrimination of those groups.
